YELLOW FEVER - SOUTH AMERICA (30): BRAZIL (RIO GRANDE DO SUL, SAO PAULO)
************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

In this update:
[1] Sao Paulo state
[2] Overview

******
[1] Sao Paulo state
Date: Wed 20 Mar 2009
Source: O Globo [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/cidades/sp/mat/2009/05/20/exame-feito-em-macaco-comprova-que-ele-morreu-de-febre-amarela-em-itapetininga-sao-paulo-755949866.asp>


The result of the analysis of a monkey found in rural Itapetininga shows
that it died of yellow fever [virus infection]. Therefore, bordering cities
have also begun to vaccinate the population. In 2008, 2 cases of yellow
fever were registered in the State of Sao Paulo and 2 people died. In 2009,
25 cases [have been] confirmed and 9 people [have died].

The howler monkey was found dead in a site in a rural area of Itapetininga.
On 27 April [2009], it was sent for analysis and it was found that it died
of yellow fever [virus infection]. From then on concerns about the disease
[virus] infecting humans began.

According to the Epidemiological Surveillance of Itapetininga, 123 580
people were immunized in the city this year [2009]. According to the
coordinator, Aguida Marcondes, there is no reason to panic. The alert is
for neighboring municipalities. The State Secretariat of Health directed 6
cities in the region to halt the virus [infection by vaccination]: Tatui,
Pilar do Sul, Capao Bonito, Sao Miguel Arcanjo, Sarapui, and Alambari.

--
